## Step 1: Vision clarity calibration

**Ask this first — it determines how much handholding the rest of the session needs.**

> **Q1. How clear is your life vision for the next few years?**
>
> A) Very clear — I know what I want, why I want it, and roughly how to get there
> B) Somewhat clear — I have a general direction and values but haven't articulated it fully
> C) Vague — I have some ideas but they feel scattered or contradictory
> D) No idea — I'm figuring it out from scratch

**Calibration rules:**
- **A → High clarity mode:** Skip leading prompts. Allow open-ended answers for most questions. Use follow-up questions to deepen and pressure-test rather than guide.
- **B → Guided mode:** Offer multiple-choice options but allow free-text additions. Ask follow-up questions to surface what they already half-know.
- **C or D → Scaffolded mode:** Lead with specific multiple-choice options at every step. Ask one small question at a time. Reflect their answers back before moving on.

Store their calibration level internally and apply it throughout.

**Mode depth rules:**
- `quick` mode: keep momentum, accept rough answers, skip optional deep probes.
- `deep` mode: ask follow-up probes for each pillar, baseline, and milestone; challenge vague goals into concrete versions.

---

## Step 2: Life pillars

> **Q2. Which areas of your life do you want to actively track and improve?**
> *(Select all that apply — you can add your own)*
>
> A) Career / professional work
> B) Fitness / physical health
> C) Social life / relationships
> D) Intellectual growth / side projects / learning
> E) Mental health / emotional wellbeing
> F) Financial health
> G) Creative expression (writing, art, music, etc.)
> H) Other: ____________

**Note:** You don't need to track everything. Most people find 3–5 pillars is the right number — enough to cover a whole life without too much overhead. If they select 6+, gently flag: "That's a lot to track simultaneously. You can always add pillars later — want to narrow to the 4–5 that matter most right now?"

Store their selected pillars. All future questions are scoped to what they selected.

---

## Step 3: The anchor

> **Q3. If you had to pick one area that is your "anchor" — the domain where you most want to be credible, skilled, and well-compensated — what would it be?**
>
> *(This doesn't mean it's the most important thing in your life. It means it's the foundation: the thing that earns you legitimacy and funding so the rest can thrive.)*
>
> A) My career / professional role
> B) Building a business or freelance practice
> C) A craft or creative skill (writing, design, code, music, etc.)
> D) Something I haven't defined yet
> E) I don't want an "anchor" — I want everything to be equal weight

**If they pick E:** Gently note: "Most people find that without one anchor, everything becomes equally urgent and nothing gets deep. But you can run the system with equal-weight pillars — it just means no 'primary grow' priority in career. Let's continue and see if something emerges."

---

## Step 4: Vision — the long version

**(Scaffolded mode: ask each sub-question separately. High clarity mode: ask as one block.)**

> **Q4. Let's build your vision.**

**4a. The 5-year version:**
> In 5 years, if things went well — not perfectly, but genuinely well — what would your life look like? Describe it in terms of what you're doing, who you're with, how you feel day-to-day.
>
> *(If you're in scaffolded mode, choose the closest answer and add any detail:)*
>
> A) I'd have a well-regarded job or career that I'm proud of and that gives me financial stability
> B) I'd be running my own thing — business, practice, or creative work — with real traction
> C) I'd have built deep expertise or a reputation in something I care about
> D) My life would feel rich in relationships, experiences, and physical vitality — even if work is not the centerpiece
> E) Something else: ____________

**4b. The deathbed version:**
> On your deathbed, what would you most want to feel proud of? What would feel like a waste?
>
> *(No multiple choice here — just answer freely.)*

In `quick` mode, make this optional if they feel blocked.

**4c. The one-line version:**
> Summarize it in one sentence: "I want to be [X], and feel [Y]."
>
> *(If they're struggling, offer:)*
> - "I want to be excellent at [anchor] and interesting across [constellation]."
> - "I want a life where I'm proud of my work AND proud of how I lived it."
> - "I want to be known for [X] and feel [Y] most days."
>
> Help them land on a one-liner. This becomes the top of their Life-Arc-Overview.

