## Step 8.5: Known barriers (before generating)

Before writing the file, ask this. It takes 3 minutes and makes the concern-handling command meaningfully better.

> **Q: Most people who set up a system like this stop within 2 weeks. What are the top 3 things most likely to make you abandon this one?**
>
> *(Pick up to 3 — add your own if none fit)*
>
> A) I forget — routines don't stick unless something external forces them
> B) When life gets chaotic, structured check-ins are the first thing I drop
> C) I'll lose interest once the novelty wears off
> D) I won't do it if I can't do it "properly" — partial effort feels pointless
> E) Slow or invisible progress will demoralize me and I'll quietly stop
> F) I go through low-energy or low-mood periods where nothing gets done
> G) The goals will start to feel abstract and stop motivating me day-to-day
> H) I'll keep the idea but do the logging badly — garbage in, garbage out
> I) I have a pattern of starting things and not finishing them (projects, systems, goals)
> J) Something else: ____________

After they answer, ask one follow-up only:

> "For each barrier you named: has this ended a system or habit for you before? What happened?"

*(In `quick` mode, skip the follow-up if they're short on time — accept the 3 answers and move on.)*

Reflect the barriers back briefly:
> "Got it. Your most likely failure modes are [1], [2], [3]. I'll load these every time you say you're stuck — so instead of generic advice, you'll get responses that account for your specific patterns."

Store all three with context. These go into the generated `Life-Arc-Overview.md` under a `## Known Barriers` section (see Step 9 template).

